+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_011mffHZELPiqCusjqrUn3aW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01MfJu4hMB1PjFXXr2QBmCWS","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"npx tsx -e '\nimport { countBeamCells, countBeamPaths } from \"./src/index.ts\";\n\n// WORST CASE for countBeamCells: many splitters that cause exponential beam count\n// Unlike countBeamPaths which merges beams with same (col,dir), countBeamCells\n// tracks individual beams in a queue. This could cause exponential blowup!\n\nconst rows = 200;\nconst cols = 200;\nconst grid: string[][] = Array.from({ length: rows }, () =>\n  Array.from({ length: cols }, () => \".\")\n);\ngrid[0][100] = \"S\";\n\n// Place splitters so beams recombine and split again\n// Put splitters at the same column, spaced apart\nfor (let i = 0; i < 50; i++) {\n  const r = 1 + i * 2;\n  if (r < rows) {\n    grid[r][100] = \"^\";\n  }\n}\n// After each split at col 100, we get DL to col 99 and DR to col 101\n// These diagonal beams go to the next row, but they wont hit the next splitter at col 100\n// So actually only the FIRST splitter is hit, then the beams diverge.\n\n// A more pathological case: splitters at alternating positions to re-merge beams\n// Source at 100, splitter at (1,100) -> DL(2,99) DR(2,101)\n// Put splitters at (3,99) and (3,101): \n//   (3,99): DL(4,98) DR(4,100)  \n//   (3,101): DL(4,100) DR(4,102)\n// Now we have 2 beams at (4,100)!\n// Put splitter at (5,100): splits both beams\n// etc.\n\n// This creates a diamond pattern that re-merges beams\nconst grid2: string[][] = Array.from({ length: rows }, () =>\n  Array.from({ length: cols }, () => \".\")\n);\ngrid2[0][100] = \"S\";\n\n// Pattern: split at center, diverge, converge back at center, repeat\n// Row 1: splitter at 100 -> beams at (2,99) DL and (2,101) DR\n// Row 3: splitters at 99 and 101 \n//   (3,99) DL from (2,99): DL(4,98) DR(4,100)\n//   But wait: beam at (2,99) has direction DL, so it goes to (3,98), not (3,99)!\n\n// Actually, after a split:\n//   DL beam is at (2,99) with direction down-left\n//   So next step: (3,98), then (4,7), etc. It keeps going down-left.\n//   DR beam is at (2,101) with direction down-right\n//   So next step: (3,102), then (4,103), etc.\n\n// For beams to reconverge, we need the DL beam to hit a splitter that sends a DR beam\n// back toward center. Lets think about this:\n\n// Source at (0,100), splitter at (1,100)\n// DL beam: (2,99) dir=DL -> (3,98) dir=DL -> ...\n// DR beam: (2,101) dir=DR -> (3,102) dir=DR -> ...\n// These never reconverge naturally. To make them reconverge:\n// Place splitter at (2,99): DL beam hits it. Creates DL(3,98) and DR(3,100)\n// Place splitter at (2,101): DR beam hits it. Creates DL(3,100) and DR(3,102)\n// Now (3,100) has TWO beams (both dir=down, from the DR of left split and DL of right split)\n// Wait no: the new beams from (2,99) splitter are DL and DR, not down.\n// From (2,99) split: DL goes to (3,98) dir=DL, DR goes to (3,100) dir=DR\n// From (2,101) split: DL goes to (3,100) dir=DL, DR goes to (3,102) dir=DR\n// At (3,100): one beam dir=DR and one beam dir=DL -- different directions!\n// These are separate beams, cannot be merged in countBeamCells\n\n// For countBeamCells, the key question is: can the queue grow exponentially?\n// Each splitter doubles the number of beams. With 50 splitters, that is 2^50 beams.\n// But countBeamCells doesnt deduplicate by (col,dir) like countBeamPaths does.\n// It uses a simple queue. If each beam independently hits splitters, we get exponential growth.\n\n// But actually, in practice, after a split the diagonal beams diverge and rarely hit \n// the same splitter. Let me construct a worst case:\n\n// If we put all splitters in a column, only the first one is hit (straight down).\n// After that, DL and DR beams go diagonally and miss the column.\n\n// For a true worst case, wed need a diamond lattice of splitters.\n// Lets try: splitters along col 100, each hit by a DR beam from the splitter above-left.\n\n// Actually, the issue is simpler: countBeamCells uses a pop-based queue.\n// Each beam is processed once and either spawns 1 or 2 new beams.\n// The total number of beam objects created = sum of beams across all rows.\n// With 50 splitters along various paths, the total beams could be up to ~2^50.\n// This would be a performance disaster for countBeamCells!\n\n// Lets test with a carefully constructed worst case.\n// 20 splitters that ALL get hit:\nconst grid3: string[][] = Array.from({ length: 100 }, () =>\n  Array.from({ length: 100 }, () => \".\")\n);\ngrid3[0][50] = \"S\";\n\n// Place splitters in a binary tree pattern\n// Row 1: col 50\n// Row 3: cols 49, 51 (hit by DL and DR from row 1)\n// But DL from (1,50) has direction DL, goes to (2,49), then (3,48)... misses (3,49)\n\n// Hmm, the diagonal beams dont converge easily. Let me try a simpler approach.\n// Put a splitter directly below S, then splitters 2 rows below at the split positions.\n// Row 0: S at col 50\n// Row 1: ^ at col 50. Splits to DL(2,49) and DR(2,51)\n//         But these beams have dir=DL and dir=DR respectively\n// Row 2: ^ at col 49. DL beam hits it. Splits to DL(3,48) and DR(3,50)\n// Row 2: ^ at col 51. DR beam hits it. Splits to DL(3,50) and DR(3,52)\n// 4 beams now. 2 at (3,50) but different dirs (DR and DL), 1 at (3,48) dir=DL, 1 at (3,52) dir=DR\n// Put splitters at (3,50), (3,48), (3,52)? But then all 4 beams hit splitters -> 8 beams.\n// Wait, (3,50) has 2 beams hitting it, each spawns 2 = 4 from that cell.\n// Plus (3,48) spawns 2, (3,52) spawns 2. Total = 8 beams.\n// Continue pattern...\n\n// Lets count how many splitters we need for K levels.\n// Level 0: 1 splitter (row 1, col 50)\n// Level 1: 2 splitters (row 2, cols 49 and 51)\n// Level 2: 3 splitters (row 3, cols 48, 50, 52)  \n// Actually it gets complicated. Let me just test with 20 levels max.\n\nlet splitterCount = 0;\n// Level 0\ngrid3[1][50] = \"^\"; splitterCount++;\n// After: DL at (2,49) dir DL, DR at (2,51) dir DR\n\n// Level 1: these beams arrive at row 2\ngrid3[2][49] = \"^\"; splitterCount++;\ngrid3[2][51] = \"^\"; splitterCount++;\n// After level 1: DL(3,48)DL, DR(3,50)DR, DL(3,50)DL, DR(3,52)DR\n// 4 beams, 3 distinct positions\n\n// Level 2: splitters where beams land on row 3\ngrid3[3][48] = \"^\"; splitterCount++;\ngrid3[3][50] = \"^\"; splitterCount++;\ngrid3[3][52] = \"^\"; splitterCount++;\n// (3,48) 1 beam -> 2; (3,50) 2 beams -> 4; (3,52) 1 beam -> 2. Total = 8 beams\n\n// This grows exponentially! After k levels, number of beams = 2^(k+1)\n// But the number of unique (col,dir) pairs grows linearly.\n// countBeamCells tracks individual beams, not merged beams!\n\n// Lets continue the pattern for more levels:\n// Level n: beams land at row (n+1), positions from 50-n to 50+n step 2\n// Each interior position gets 2 beams (from DL above-right and DR above-left)\n// Each edge position gets 1 beam\n\nfunction placeLevel(row: number, centerCol: number, halfWidth: number) {\n  for (let i = -halfWidth; i <= halfWidth; i++) {\n    const c = centerCol + i * 2;\n    if (c >= 0 && c < 100 && row < 100) {\n      if (grid3[row][c] === \".\") {\n        grid3[row][c] = \"^\";\n        splitterCount++;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n\n// We already placed levels 0-2. Continue from level 3.\nfor (let level = 3; level < 20; level++) {\n  const row = level + 1;\n  const halfWidth = level;\n  placeLevel(row, 50, halfWidth);\n}\n\nconsole.log(\"Splitter count:\", splitterCount);\n\nconst start = performance.now();\nconst cellResult = countBeamCells(grid3);\nconst elapsed = performance.now() - start;\nconsole.log(\"countBeamCells result:\", cellResult, \"elapsed:\", elapsed.toFixed(2), \"ms\");\n\nconst start2 = performance.now();\nconst pathResult = countBeamPaths(grid3);\nconst elapsed2 = performance.now() - start2;\nconsole.log(\"countBeamPaths result:\", pathResult, \"elapsed:\", elapsed2.toFixed(2), \"ms\");\n' 2>&1\n","des